<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18571026-1137">
               <interp inst="t18571026-1137" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18571026"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18571026-1137" type="date" value="18571026"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18571026-1137-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1137-18571026 t18571026-1137-offence-1 t18571026-1137-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18571026-1137-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-1137-18571026 t18571026-1137-offence-1 t18571026-1137-verdict-2"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18571026-1137-charge-3" targOrder="Y" targets="def3-1137-18571026 t18571026-1137-offence-1 t18571026-1137-verdict-3"></join>
               <p>1137. <persName id="def1-1137-18571026" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1137-18571026" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1137-18571026" type="surname" value="MARTIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1137-18571026" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">CHARLES MARTIN</hi>
                  </persName>, <persName id="def2-1137-18571026" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-1137-18571026" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1137-18571026" type="surname" value="BARKER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1137-18571026" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">THOMAS BARKER</hi>
                  </persName>, and <persName id="def3-1137-18571026" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def3-1137-18571026" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-1137-18571026" type="surname" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-1137-18571026" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOSEPH JAMES</hi>
                  </persName>, <rs id="t18571026-1137-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18571026-1137-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18571026-1137-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp>Stealing 100 gallons of oil, value 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18571026-name-804" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-804" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-804" type="surname" value="GARDNER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-804" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18571026-1137-offence-1 t18571026-name-804"></join>William Gardner</persName>, the master of Martin and Barker.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. METCALFE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">SALTER</hi>. <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-805" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-805" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-805" type="surname" value="WHITT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-805" type="given" value="PETER"></interp>PETER WHITT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am mate on board the <hi rend="italic">Pollux</hi> steam vessel. On 16th Sept. we had on board 32 casks of linseed oil—I took them in at Hamburgh—when we arrived at London they were put into a barge—I do not recollect the name of it—I noticed the casks at the time I took them out—I did not see any spile holes in them at that time—they are usually at the top or bottom of the cask—I did not notice any such holes as these(<hi rend="italic">Looking at some spile holes in the head of a cask</hi>) at the time they left the vessel—I cannot recollect seeing either of the prisoners in the barge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was this separation in the head of a cask when it left? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I did not look for spile holes—some casks were leaky, not very leaky—there was one cask that had not much oil in it; I cannot tell how much—I saw that they had been leaking—the casks were put into the barge with slings—we generally use sling whether the cash are good or bad—I saw that the oil had been leaking from those casks—I examined the hold afterwards; I did not find any quantity of oil there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long had the casks been in that hold? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About five days.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RIBTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How many casks were moved into the barge? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Thirty-two—about ten men were assisting in moving them from the Pollux into the barge—they were lifted up by machinery, and slung down into the barge—they were rolled into the barge—the next cask would knock against the other—we took them on board at Hamburgh—I do not know where we got them from—I cannot tell whether the casks were full; I did not examine them—we were five days in coming—it was not during the equinoctial gales—we had a good passage—it was not blowing hard—it was at Horselydown that we moved the casks from the Pollux into the barge—our vessel was 250 tons—we had a general cargo.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-806" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-806" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-806" type="surname" value="MORGAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-806" type="given" value="ROBERT HENRY"></interp>ROBERT HENRY MORGAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a tide surveyor. On 16th Sept. I was on duty on board the Pollux steamer—I saw a number of casks of linseed oil—I examined four of them—I found them sound—I do not know whether the others were sound or not—I saw the whole of them—I did not observe any unsoundness, except in one cask, which was leaking at the head very much—it was leaking round the chine at the edge—there was no leakage from spile holes like these—I called attention to that particular cask—I saw some of the casks put into the barge, perhaps four or five—I did not see any of those leak, only the one—I mentioned to the mate to put it in a</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185710260200"></xptr>
               <p>certain position, with the head upwards, or it would leak all out, and it was put so.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you go into the barge? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I do not remember how they were packed in the barge—I do not remem<lb></lb>ber whether they were all in the bottom of the barge or not—I selected four of them, and made a full examination of them, to see if there was any in them subject to duty—I ascertained what was in them by taking bung out and putting a stick in—I did not make any spile holes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-807" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-807" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-807" type="surname" value="GARDNER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-807" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM GARDNER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a lighterman, and live in Horselydown. The barge <hi rend="italic">Miskin</hi> was in my employ—on 15th Sept. I gave directions that it should be taken to the <hi rend="italic">Pollux</hi> to take the oil—Martin was my foreman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was it a barge that was hired? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—Martin has been in my employ fifteen months—I believed him to be a man of good character—I know nothing against his character—he had no authority to hire anybody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-808" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-808" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-808" type="surname" value="TOON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-808" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS TOON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am foreman to Messrs. Wheeler and Co., wharfingers, at Casson's Wharf. On 18th Sept. I remember a number of casks of oil coming to the dock—I noticed them, and I observed there were spile holes, and they were leaking—the spile holes were at the head part, at either end—a great many of them appeared to have been recently made—they had been made with a common sized gimlet—I gave directions to have the whole of the casks weighed—there were thirty-two casks.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You gave directions to two persons to clean the barge out? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I first saw it on Friday, 18th Sept., about 5 or 6 o'clock in the evening—I did not see any one with the barge—it was on the side of the wharf—it was brought there on Friday evening, and left there—it had not been there more than half an hour—I had been there all day backwards and forwards—I came back, and saw the barge—I had left the same place about an hour—there was nobody with the barge—it remained till the next morning.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-809" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-809" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-809" type="surname" value="TILLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-809" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM TILLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at No. 5, King Street, Horselydownn; I am in the employ of Messrs. Wheeler and Co. On 19th Sept. a lighter came to me to be unloaded—I noticed the casks in it—several casks were leaking from great spile holes—I noticed spile holes in nine or ten casks, and there was a good drop of oil in the barge—I was ordered to go down and scoop the oil up and put it into a cask—there was water with it—I got up some<lb></lb>where about 100 gallons of oil and water together—I cannot tell what quantity of water there was—we scooped up all the oil we could find on the top of the water—when we got it into the cask there was much water with it—the oil was on the top of the water—I saw the barge taken away by Shorter—before that I had cleared all the oil I could see—the cabin was shut, and there was a padlock on the door—I did not look inside the cabin.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was there not any hole that you could look through into the cabin? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—I mean to swear there was a lock on tie cabin—I did not try it—I was not anxious to get into the cabin—I saw there was a padlock on it—I swept the bottom of the barge—I did not take up the floor—I was never under the boards of the barge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-810" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-810" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-810" type="surname" value="RICKMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-810" type="given" value="JOHN JAMES"></interp>JOHN JAMES RICKMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I was with the last witness when he was scooping up the oil—I did not notice the cabin door—I did not see the barge till Saturday.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-811" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-811" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-811" type="surname" value="PATTISON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-811" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM PATTISON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the employ of Messrs. Wheeler and Co—I did not see the oil come—I noticed ten of the casks had spile holes, which were open—some spile holes were filled up, and some were not—some</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185710260201"></xptr>
               <p>had been put in previous to their coming to the scale—I took the weights—I have a copy of it here, 35, 023 lbs.—I found one cask in which wag a great deficiency, No. 164; it was not a quarter fall—there were two spile holes in the head of the cask, and one spile hole in the quarter—these holes had been stopped up—it was a sound cask independent of the spile holes—it did not appear to have leaked from any other part—ten casks were not full.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You examined the whole of the casks? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I found one cask leaking from the head, and that one was get up on the end—there might have been about 5 cwt. in that cask, and that cask might hold about 14 cwt.—it was about one-third full—I will swear there was more than 2 cwt. or 3 cwt. in it—one cask we looked at had only about half it should have had, provided it had been full.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-812" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-812" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-812" type="surname" value="BALSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-812" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>DANIEL BALSON</persName>
                  </hi>. On 19th Sept. I saw thirty-two casks of oil on the wharf—some had holes in them, and they were very shakey casks, and leak<lb></lb>ing at both ends—there were spile holes in them—I think I perceived spile holes in about eight of them—they were in the head—two of the holes in one cask had spiles in them, the others had not—I stopped them up with spiles.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> What do you mean by shakey? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They were in a bad state—I am in the service of Messrs. Wheeler—the casks were taken out of the barge by slings—that is usual when they are not in good condition—when they are, they are taken out with the hooks—I noticed some casks leaking besides those with the spiles—there might be six or seven leaking from natural causes—they had been old wine pipes before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Would those which were leaking without the spile holes leak as much as 200 gallons? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Ye, more than that in the barge—I do not know how long they were in the barge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you mean that the casks might have leaked 200 gallons from what injury you saw they had sustained, independent of the spile holes? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, from the slightness of the casks—there was a little got out by Toon—there might be 16 cwt. or 17 cwt.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RIBTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You say these casks were wine casks? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They seemed so—they were not new—how many times they had been used in the wine trade I do not know.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-813" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-813" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-813" type="surname" value="EVEREST"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-813" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD EVEREST</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">Themes police inspector</hi>). On Sunday, 20th Sept, I was on duty in my boat about half past 11 o'clock. I saw the prisoner Barker on board the <hi rend="italic">Miskin</hi> barge, at Bermondsey, about 400 yards from Pearson's wharf—he was scooping up oil, and placing it in two small casks, about seven or eight gallons each—I went on board the barge—one or two of the floor boards were taken, up, and he was scooping the oil from between the timbers of the barge—I asked him what he was doing—he said "Scoop<lb></lb>ing up some oil"—I asked him what authority he had to scoop it up—he said, "Martin gave it me"—I asked him what authority Martin had to give it him, and he said he did not know—I left a constable in charge of him, and I went to another barge close by, where I found a cask containing about ten gallons of the same description of oil—I came back to the <hi rend="italic">Miskin</hi> barge in about ten minutes afterwards, and I found all the three prisoners there—I found in the cabin three larger casks, and three cans full of oil—I asked Barker what he had done with the oil he landed in the morning—he said he had sold it to Harradine—I asked how much there was—he said, "About twenty-four gallons"—I asked if there was any one there who had tad part of that with him, and James made answer, "Yes, Martin"—Martin made answer, "Yes; I gave it to him, it is only drainings; it is an</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185710260202"></xptr>
               <p>every day occurrence"—the cabin was open when I went—when I took Barker I took a key from him which he said he had had to lock the cabin—I then went to Mr. Gardner, and Martin went with me—Mr. Gardner came back with us, and I took James and Barker into custody—in the afternoon, I went to Harradine's house about half past 3 o'clock—he is a marine store dealer—I there found two ten gallon cans full of oil, and a cask holding from thirty to thirty-six gallons besides—there was very little water mixed with it, and very little dirt—I have samples from the different places—this one is from that that was in the cask at Mr. Harradine's—this is from the cans found on board the barge—this other is from the cask on board the barge—I found seventy gallons on board the barge, and fifty-two gallons at Harradine's—I went to James's house on Sunday night, and he met me at the door—I told him I wanted to see what he had got in his house—I went in, and saw Martin sitting there—he said, "Halloo! Mr. Everest, I have just come to have an understanding about this oil"—I satisfied myself that there was no oil on the premises, and I called Martin out and took him into custody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You first saw Barker? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I do not know that in consequence of what I said Martin was fetched—James lives about ten minutes' walk from there—I asked if any one had had part, and James said, "Yes, it was only drainings, it is an every day occurrence."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RIBTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> On what day did you see James? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> On Sunday, about half past 1 o'clock—I was at his house the same night about 8 o'clock—he had been bailed out by the inspector—Martin is fore<lb></lb>man to Mr. Gardner—I took Martin into custody, and he went down to the station—he did not say that he knew nothing about it, and he was only acting under direction—there was about seventy gallons found on board—there had been a good deal of leakage, being old casks.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You found some oil on board another barge? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; about ten gallons—the barge was all saturated with oil—the barge would not require a great deal of cleaning.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RIBTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you really mean to pledge your oath that James did not say to you words to this effect, that Martin had given him authority to remove the oil? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; the only answer he made when I asked if any person had any part of that was, "Yes, Martin"—I took him on the Miskin barge—I told him I should take him into custody for having possession of the oil.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-814" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-814" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-814" type="surname" value="HARRADINE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-814" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES HARRADINE</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at No. 88, Dockhead. I gave up the cans of oil to the police—I received them from James and Barker, on 19th Sept., about half past 4 o'clock—I paid 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a gallon for it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-815" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-815" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-815" type="surname" value="GARDNER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-815" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM GARDNER</persName>
                  </hi>. <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> Martin was my foreman—I know nothing of James—it would be part of my foreman's duty to superintend the cargo of oil—he would not have to pay for the barge—the bill would come to me—I have not carried much oil; two or three parcels in three months—they are all carried in barges—the <hi rend="italic">Miskin</hi> may have had other cargoes of oil in it—I have not received the bill yet—the owner of the barge is Henry Dug<lb></lb>gan—I never had oil conveyed in his barge before—my men would not have any right to take any leakage—if there had been a small leakage of two or three gallons I should take no notice of it—I do not claim any leakage—that leakage would be such as would not be worth the consignee's notice—if a barge is hired and it gets into a mess with leakage I should not have to clean it, I should return it in it's dirty state—if the men had informed me</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185710260203"></xptr>
               <p>that 100 gallons of oil was left in the barge I should have referred it to the wharfinger.</p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">Martin and James received good characters.</hi>)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">MARTIN</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18571026-1137-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-1137-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-1137-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value=""></interp>NOT GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">BARKER</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18571026-1137-verdict-2" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-1137-verdict-2" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-1137-verdict-2" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>.—<hi rend="italic">
                     <rs id="t18571026-1137-punishment-125" type="punishmentDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-1137-punishment-125" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-1137-punishment-125" type="punishmentSubcategory" value="penalServitude"></interp>
                        <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-1137-18571026 t18571026-1137-punishment-125"></join>Four Tears Penal Servitude.</rs>
                  </hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">JAMES</hi>—
<rs id="t18571026-1137-verdict-3" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18571026-1137-verdict-3" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18571026-1137-verdict-3" type="verdictSubcategory" value="withRecommendation"></interp>
                     <hi rend="smallCaps">GUILTY</hi>.—<hi rend="italic">Recommended to mercy by the Jury.</hi>
                  </rs>
                  <hi rend="italic">—
<rs id="t18571026-1137-punishment-126" type="punishmentDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-1137-punishment-126" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
